Subject:    <a href="?t=92599971900002&r=1&w=2">Nicknames</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837661700001&r=1&w=2">Peter Karp &lt;KARP () SUMEX-AIM ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198505">1985-05-01 15:34:49</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426409&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426409&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I believe recent messages have confused two concepts which should
be treated quite distinctly: nicknames and abreviations.  

A nickname is a full domain name which is stored in one or more domain
servers and which translates (via CNAME records) into the official name for
a given resource.  I believe that the purpose of nicknames should be to
allow a many-to-one mapping between names and resources, rather than
requring a one-to-one mapping.  The previously mentionned CSNet example
illustrates one circumstance in which this ability is desireable.  Use
of nicknames is dependent upon decisions about the design of domain
servers and the contents of their databases.

Abreviations are intended to make it easier to type the name of a
resource.  Abreviations are needed because domain names (of which
nicknames are a subset) are usually long strings.  I believe that the
use of abreviations should be facilitated through the design of user
interfaces (resolvers, mail programs, telnet programs), not domain
servers.

Obviously one can hack domain servers to include abreviations, but I
think this is a bad idea, mainly because it is not computationally
feasible.  Let's make user interfaces better by writing better user
interfaces, not by thinking about transferring huge zones between
servers or about doing network broadcasts.

Peter
